":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Kleve","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: habitational name from Kleve (earlier Cleve) in Lower Rhineland, Westphalia, or Schleswig-Holstein. The placename probably derives from an old topographic term <i>cleve</i> ‘swamp’. Compare   Cleve  .","German: variant of   Klever   2.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads named Kleiva, from Old Norse <i>kleif</i>, <i>klif</i> ‘cliff, rocky ascent with a road or path’."],"variants":[{"name":"Klever","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Kurt, Ulrike.","German and Dutch: habitational name for someone from Kleve in the Rhineland or Schleswig-Holstein (see   Kleve   1).","German: from Middle Low German <i>klēver</i> ‘clover, meadow’, also ‘resin, turpentine’, hence a metonymic occupational name either for a farmer who grew clover or for someone who collected resin and distilled turpentine. In the Alemannic area this was also a nickname for a bungler. Compare   Cleaver   and   Clever  ."]},{"name":"Kleven","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Berger, Hjalmer, Jalmer, Knute, Maren, Obert, Thor, Thorval.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads all over Norway named Kleven, from the definite singular form of   Kleve  . Compare   Cleven   and   Cleveland  .","Dutch and German: rare variant of   Cleven  ."]},{"name":"Cleve","meanings":["English: variant of   Cliff  .","German: variant of   Kleve  ."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilde von Kleve was born in 1166, in Roma, Lazio, Italy, her father, Dietrich IV. von Kleve, was 37 and her mother, Adelheid von Sulzbach, was 32. She married Arnold von Altena-Isenberg in 1180. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1166–":"1166–Surnud","1164–1198":"1164–1198","1166–Female":"1166–Surnud","1167–1242":"1167–1242","1171–1200":"1171–1200","1166–1209":"1166–1209","1182–1226":"1182–1226","1186–1217":"1186–1217","1129–1172":"1129–1172","1135–1189":"1135–1189","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1186":"1186","1164":"1164","1172":"1172","1182":"1182","1171":"1171","1180":"1180","1129":"1129","1217":"1217","1226":"1226","1135":"1135","1189":"1189","1200":"1200","1167":"1167","1166":"1166","1209":"1209","about 1186":"umbes 1186","Rome":"Roma, Lazio, Itaalia","Hövel, Kreis Arnsberg, Westphalia, Prussia, German Empire":"Hövel, Arnsberg, Provinz Westfalen, Preußen","Burg Altena, Altena, Märkischer Kreis, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Deutschland":"Altena, Märkischer Kreis, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1166–":"1166–Kuollut","1164–1198